======================================================================
PART 3: ROOT COUNTS AND THE PERMANENT MOAT
======================================================================

  Root count dictionary:
    |Phi+(A1)| =    1 (mod 7 = 1)
    |Phi+(A2)| =    3 (mod 7 = 3)
    |Phi+(A3)| =    6 (mod 7 = 6)
    |Phi+(A4)| =   10 (mod 7 = 3)
    |Phi+(D4)| =   12 (mod 7 = 5) = h(E6) = h(F4)
    |Phi+(A5)| =   15 (mod 7 = 1)
    |Phi+(D5)| =   20 (mod 7 = 6)
    |Phi+(A6)| =   21 (mod 7 = 0) = H_forb_2 = Phi3(KEY1^2)
    |Phi+(A7)| =   28 (mod 7 = 0) = C(8,2) = C(rank(E8),2)
    |Phi+(D6)| =   30 (mod 7 = 2)
    |Phi+(E6)| =   30 (mod 7 = 2)
    |Phi+(E7)| =   42 (mod 7 = 0)
    |Phi+(E8)| =   56 (mod 7 = 0)

  KEY OBSERVATION:
    |Phi+(E7)| = 63 = 7 * 9 = H_forb_1 * KEY_2^2
    |Phi+(E8)| = 120 = |BI| = 8 * 15 = rank(E8) * E(Petersen)
    |Phi+(E7)| / |Phi+(E6)| = 63/36 = 7/4 = H_forb_1 / KEY_1^2
    |Phi+(E8)| / |Phi+(E7)| = 120/63 = 40/21 = 40/H_forb_2

======================================================================
PART 4: INFORMATION THEORY OF TOURNAMENTS
======================================================================

  Tournament on n vertices: C(n,2) binary choices.
  Total information content: C(n,2) bits = log2(2^C(n,2)) bits.

  n=3: 3 edges, 8 tournaments
    Information content: 3 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 3

  n=4: 6 edges, 64 tournaments
    Information content: 6 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 6

  n=5: 10 edges, 1024 tournaments
    Information content: 10 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 10

  n=6: 15 edges, 32768 tournaments
    Information content: 15 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 15

  n=7: 21 edges, 2097152 tournaments
    Information content: 21 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 21

  n=8: 28 edges, 268435456 tournaments
    Information content: 28 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 28

  n=9: 36 edges, 68719476736 tournaments
    Information content: 36 bits
    log2(#tournaments) = 36

  Shannon entropy of H distribution:
    n=5: H(dist) = 2.6810 bits (out of 10.0000 max)
    n=6: H(dist) = 4.0502 bits (out of 15.0000 max)
    n=6: max entropy = log2(19) = 4.2479 bits (19 distinct H values)
    n=6: efficiency = 0.9534

  Information loss: tournament -> H(T)
    n=5: 10 bits -> 2.81 bits (0.2807 retained, 7.19 lost)
    n=6: 15 bits -> 4.25 bits (0.2832 retained, 10.75 lost)

======================================================================
PART 5: TOURNAMENTS AS QUIVERS
======================================================================

  A tournament T on n vertices is a QUIVER Q_T:
    - Vertices: {1, ..., n} (not to be confused with quiver rep vertices)
    - Arrows: one arrow i -> j for each pair (i,j) based on tournament orientation

  The PATH ALGEBRA kQ_T has basis = all directed paths in T.
  For tournaments: every pair connected, so many paths exist.

  KEY DIFFERENCE from Dynkin quivers:
    - Tournament quivers are COMPLETE (every pair has an arrow)
    - Dynkin quivers are SPARSE (tree-like)
    - Tournament quivers have WILD representation type for n >= 3
      (infinitely many indecomposables, not parameterizable)

  But: the CYCLE STRUCTURE of Q_T connects to H(T) via OCF!
    - Directed odd cycles in Q_T = vertices of Omega(T)
    - H(T) = I(Omega(T), 2) = independence polynomial at x=2
    
======================================================================
PART 6: McKAY QUIVERS — ADE CORRESPONDENCE
======================================================================

  McKay correspondence: finite G < SU(2) <-> affine ADE diagram

  The McKay quiver has:
    - Vertices = irreducible reps of G
    - Arrows encode tensor product with fundamental 2-dim rep

  For the three exceptional subgroups:
    BT (binary tetrahedral, |BT|=24): McKay quiver = affine E_6 (7 vertices)
    BO (binary octahedral, |BO|=48):  McKay quiver = affine E_7 (8 vertices)
    BI (binary icosahedral, |BI|=120): McKay quiver = affine E_8 (9 vertices)

  Affine E_n has n+1 vertices (adding the extending node to E_n).

  DIMENSIONS of irreps (= components of null vector of affine Cartan):
    
  BT irrep dimensions: [1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3]
    Sum of squares: 24 = |BT| = 24
    Number of irreps: 7 = rank(E6)+1 = 7
    Sum of dims: 12 = h(E6) = 12

  BO irrep dimensions: [1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 2, 4]
    Sum of squares: 48 = |BO| = 48
    Number of irreps: 8 = rank(E7)+1 = 8
    Sum of dims: 18 = h(E7) = 18

  BI irrep dimensions: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 4, 2, 3]
    Sum of squares: 120 = |BI| = 120
    Number of irreps: 9 = rank(E8)+1 = 9
    Sum of dims: 30 = h(E8) = 30

